{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e15562b0-8295-4d26-9fd7-46d0bb2cce94","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI property — that's likely why it has no effect. Here's what you need:\n\n**XAML:**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             Padding=\"0\">\n    <Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n        <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n               Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Key fixes:**\n\n1. **iOS** — Use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` (the platform-specific property)\n2. **Layout** — Set `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the containing Grid/layout\n3. **Page** — Ensure `Padding=\"0\"` explicitly\n4. **Android** — On .NET 10 targeting Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced automatically. For older API levels, add this in your `MainActivity`:\n\n```csharp\nMicrosoft.Maui.ApplicationModel.Platform.ActivityStateChanged += (s, e) => { };\n// In OnCreate, after base call:\nWindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n```\n\nThe combination of `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` (iOS) + `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` (layout) + no padding is what gives you true edge-to-edge content.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f50ac629-3b4c-4fb0-8641-d8ea85242bef","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is building a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common issue in .NET MAUI. Setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` isn't sufficient by itself. The key things they're likely missing:\n\n1. **`IgnoreSafeArea`** - In .NET MAUI, views respect safe areas by default. You need to set `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the layout or the Image itself.\n\n\n2. On **iOS**, there's a platform-specific property `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` that needs to be set.\n3. On **Android**, system bars require different handling—potentially using `Edge2Edge` or configuring the window to draw behind system bars.\n\nFor .NET 9 and later, MAUI introduced improved edge-to-edge support, so the approach depends on which version they're actually targeting.\n\nThe user is probably missing a few key pieces: they need to add the iOS platform namespace and set `UseSafeArea` to false, handle Android's edge-to-edge rendering which is now more integrated, and use `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on their layout elements to tell them to disregard safe area insets.\n\nWait, I'm realizing the user mentioned `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` which isn't actually a standard .NET MAUI property on ContentPage—they might be mixing up properties from a different framework or using something custom. The real properties I should focus on are `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` for iOS and `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` for layouts, plus handling Android's edge-to-edge APIs in .NET 9 and later. The key is removing any non-existent SafeAreaEdges property, then disabling safe area handling on iOS with the platform-specific attribute, setting zero padding on the page itself, and applying `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` to the image or its container—Android might require additional platform-level configuration for edge-to-edge rendering.","outputTokens":1436,"requestId":"6C17:117C6C:7A4B35:825247:6A0AF4F3"},"id":"ad6b4559-d60a-4a8f-bbf7-657df1615315","timestamp":"2026-05-18T11:16:33.169Z","parentId":"85db535c-f436-4e6c-9170-9b5f0792e4d9"}
